Core of the argument.

The international division of labor has been developed to a point of unsustainable fragility. Biological systems, in strong contrast, have massive redundancy -- because that makes them tougher, and existence is hard. Guess what, human civilizations are still biological systems, and existence is still hard. Complex socioeconomic systems will correct accordingly. ...

... Note that increasing systemic redundancy by parallelizing elaborate supply-chains has nothing much to do with central planning. The same essential process in biology (ecology) is radically decentralized. It's almost decentralization itself.

No serious country could tolerate an international trading system that is incompatible with full supply-chain autonomy for the most advanced weapon systems currently in existence. 'Cutting-edge robotics' is a safe proxy. Next-phase of the planetary techno-industrial eco-system will follow from this.
Every cell in your body has a full copy of your entire genome. Over-enthusiastic division-of-labor liberals are now completely face-palming at that.
